Install and load required packages

> # install three R packages first. 
> install.packages(c("psych", "Hmisc", "graphics", "car", "utils", "lm.beta"), dependencies=TRUE)
> 
> 
> # load all three packages before running the model. 
> require("psych")
> require("Hmisc")
> require("graphics")
> require("car")
> require("utils")
> require("interp")
> require("lm.beta")

Example dataset

Regress achievement in social studies (ssachiev) on self esteem (selfest) and locus of control (locus) while controlling for family background (famback) and students’ previous achievement (preach). Data is in L3.txt.

> # Read dataset and save it as "l2". 
> l3=read.table("L3.txt", sep="", header=TRUE, quote="\"'")
> names(l3) #show variable names
## [1] "famback"  "preach"   "locus"    "selfest"  "ssachiev"
> head(l3) # inspect the dataset
> psych::describe(l3) # descriptive statistics
> #####################################################################
>

> # intercept (b0=35.52): The expected ssachieve is 35.52 when all predictors are zero, 
> #which was statistically significant (t(882) = 28.98, p < .01).
> # slope (b1 = 3.69): SSachieve is expected to be increased by 3.69 of a score, 
> #for every additional increase in famback, after controlling for other variables, which was statistically significant (t(882) = 9.77, p < .01).
> # slope (b2=5.15): SSachieve is expected to be increased by 5.15 of a score, 
> #for every additional increase in preach, after controlling for other variables, which was statistically significant (t(882) = 12.91, p < .01).
> #slope (b3=1.55): SSachieve is expected to be increased by 1.55 of a score, 
> #for every additional increase in locus, after controlling for other variables, which was statistically significant (t(882) = 2.81, p = .006).
> #slope (b4=0.22): SSachieve is expected to be increased by 0.22 of a score, 
> #for every additional increase in selfest, after controlling for other variables, which was not statistically significant (t(882) = 0.44, p= .66).
> 
> 
> # The overall model is statistically significant (F(4,113) = 113, p < .01). 
> # The R-squared value of .34 suggests that 34% of variance in ssachieve was explained by the model.  
>

WRITE-UP

The overall model is statistically significant (F(4,113) = 113, p < .01), suggesting that at least one predictor is significant. The R-squared value of .34 suggests that 34% of variance in ssachieve was explained by the model. The intercept was statistically significant (t(882) = 28.98, p < .01), with unstandardized cofficient of 35.52, which suggests that the expected ssachieve is 35.52 when all predictors are zero. All predictors except selfest are found to be significant. Specifically, SSachieve is expected to be increased by 3.69 of a score, for every additional increase in famback, after controlling for other variables, which was statistically significant (t(882) = 9.77, p < .01). SSachieve is expected to be increased by 5.15 of a score, for every additional increase in preach, after controlling for other variables, which was statistically significant (t(882) = 12.91, p < .01). SSachieve is expected to be increased by 1.55 of a score, for every additional increase in locus, after controlling for other variables, which was statistically significant (t(882) = 2.81, p = .006).SSachieve is expected to be increased by 0.22 of a score, for every additional increase in selfest, after controlling for other variables, which was not statistically significant (t(882) = 0.44, p= .66).

> #run hierachical models
> mreg1=lm(ssachiev~famback, data=l3) #run hierachical models - model 1
> mreg2=lm(ssachiev~famback+preach, data=l3) #run hierachical models - model 2
> mreg3=lm(ssachiev~famback+preach+locus, data=l3) #run hierachical models - model 3
> mreg4=lm(ssachiev~famback+preach+locus+selfest, data=l3) #run hierachical models - model 4

> anova(mreg1, mreg2, mreg3, mreg4)

Write-up The adding preach to model 1 is found to explain significantly more variance in an outcome (F(1, 884) = 190.91, p < .05), suggesting model 2 doea have better fit than model1. The adding locus to model 2 is found to explain significantly more variance in an outcome (F(1, 883) = 13.78, p =.0002), suggesting model 3 does have better fit than model2. The adding locus to model 3 is not found to explain significantly more variance in an outcome (F(1, 882) = .19, p =.66), suggesting model 4 does not have better fit than model3. Therefore, model 3 was selected as the final model.

Write-up Model 3 was found to be statistically significant (F(3,883) = 151, p < .05). The R-squared value was .34, suggestign that 34% of variance in an outcome was explained by famback, preach, and locus. All predictors were found to be statistically significiant. Of all predictors, preach (beta = .38) does have the strongest effect on an outcome, follwoed by famback (beta=.29) and locus (beta = .11).
